+# Online RMSProp spectral tracking theorem
+
+This note is the next bridge after the frozen-RMSProp theorem.  The frozen
+result showed that a burn-in estimate of the coordinate gradient second moment
+satisfies
+
+\[
+\widehat v_i \asymp c_e \lambda_i,
+\qquad
+c_e=\sigma^2+\|\bar w-w^\star\|_H^2,
+\]
+
+so the frozen RMSProp preconditioner is spectrally equivalent to
+
+\[
+(\widehat v_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\asymp
+c_e^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/c_e)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+This note proves the corresponding **online population tracking theorem**:
+RMSProp's exponential moving average tracks a time-varying scalar multiple of
+\(\lambda_i\).  Therefore online RMSProp behaves, at the level of its
+instantaneous spectrum, like a time-varying damped spectral preconditioner
+
+\[
+(H+\rho_t I)^{-1/2},
+\qquad
+\rho_t\simeq \epsilon/(\sigma^2+\|w_t-w^\star\|_H^2).
+\]
+
+The theorem is deliberately stated first for the population EMA.  This isolates
+the mechanism from heavy-tail concentration issues.  A final section gives the
+empirical/concentration event under which raw or robust RMSProp inherits the same
+spectral equivalence.
+
+---
+
+## 1. Setup
+
+Work in the population covariance eigenbasis.  Let
+
+\[
+x_t\sim \mathcal N(0,H),
+\qquad
+H=\operatorname{diag}(\lambda_i),
+\]
+
+and
+
+\[
+y_t=\langle x_t,w^\star\rangle+\xi_t,
+\qquad
+\mathbb E[\xi_t]=0,
+\qquad
+\mathbb E[\xi_t^2]=\sigma^2,
+\]
+
+with \(\xi_t\) independent of \(x_t\).  Let \(\mathcal F_t\) be the sigma-field
+containing all randomness before drawing \((x_t,y_t)\), so \(w_t\) is
+\(\mathcal F_t\)-measurable.  Define
+
+\[
+e_t:=w_t-w^\star,
+\qquad
+c_t:=\sigma^2+\|e_t\|_H^2.
+\]
+
+The single-sample squared-loss gradient is
+
+\[
+g_t=(\langle x_t,e_t\rangle-\xi_t)x_t.
+\]
+
+Coordinate \(i\) is
+
+\[
+g_{t,i}=(\langle x_t,e_t\rangle-\xi_t)x_{t,i}.
+\]
+
+The online RMSProp second moment is
+
+\[
+v_{t+1,i}=\beta_2 v_{t,i}+(1-\beta_2)g_{t,i}^2,
+\qquad
+0\le \beta_2<1.
+\]
+
+The corresponding preconditioner is
+
+\[
+P_{t+1,i}=(v_{t+1,i}+\epsilon)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+For the proof, introduce the population/predictable second moment
+
+\[
+\nu_{t,i}:=\mathbb E[g_{t,i}^2\mid \mathcal F_t]
+\]
+
+and the population RMSProp EMA
+
+\[
+m_{t+1,i}=\beta_2 m_{t,i}+(1-\beta_2)\nu_{t,i},
+\qquad
+m_{0,i}=0.
+\]
+
+Also define the scalar EMA
+
+\[
+d_{t+1}=\beta_2 d_t+(1-\beta_2)c_t,
+\qquad
+d_0=0.
+\]
+
+Bias correction can be applied by replacing \(m_t,d_t\) with
+\(m_t/(1-\beta_2^t),d_t/(1-\beta_2^t)\).  Since both are divided by the same
+scalar, all constant-factor spectral equivalences below are unchanged.  To keep
+notation light, we work with the uncorrected quantities.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Recalled identity: coordinate gradient second moments
+
+The frozen-RMSProp note proved the following identity.  Conditional on
+\(\mathcal F_t\),
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\nu_{t,i}
+=\mathbb E[g_{t,i}^2\mid \mathcal F_t]
+=\lambda_i(\sigma^2+\|e_t\|_H^2)+2\lambda_i^2e_{t,i}^2.
+}
+\]
+
+Equivalently,
+
+\[
+\nu_{t,i}=\lambda_i(c_t+2r_{t,i}),
+\qquad
+r_{t,i}:=\lambda_i e_{t,i}^2.
+\]
+
+Since
+
+\[
+0\le r_{t,i}\le \sum_j\lambda_j e_{t,j}^2\le c_t,
+\]
+
+we have the uniform bound
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\lambda_i c_t
+\le
+\nu_{t,i}
+\le
+3\lambda_i c_t.
+}
+\]
+
+This bound is the only probabilistic identity needed for the online tracking
+theorem.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Main theorem: population online RMSProp tracks the spectrum
+
+### Theorem 1: population RMSProp spectral tracking
+
+For every time \(t\ge 0\) and coordinate \(i\),
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\lambda_i d_t
+\le
+m_{t,i}
+\le
+3\lambda_i d_t.
+}
+\]
+
+Consequently, the population RMSProp preconditioner
+
+\[
+P^{\rm pop}_{t,i}:=(m_{t,i}+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\]
+
+satisfies
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\frac1{\sqrt 3}\,d_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/d_t)^{-1/2}
+\le
+P^{\rm pop}_{t,i}
+\le
+d_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/d_t)^{-1/2}
+}
+\]
+
+whenever \(d_t>0\).  Thus population online RMSProp is spectrally equivalent to
+
+a time-varying damped \(q=1/2\) preconditioner
+
+\[
+P^{\rm pop}_{t,i}\asymp d_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2},
+\qquad
+\rho_t:=\epsilon/d_t.
+\]
+
+### Proof
+
+The proof is an induction using the coordinate second-moment identity.
+
+At \(t=0\), both \(m_{0,i}\) and \(d_0\) are zero, so the claim holds.  Suppose
+
+\[
+\lambda_i d_t\le m_{t,i}\le 3\lambda_i d_t.
+\]
+
+Using
+
+\[
+\lambda_i c_t\le \nu_{t,i}\le 3\lambda_i c_t,
+\]
+
+we get
+
+\[
+\begin{aligned}
+m_{t+1,i}
+&=\beta_2m_{t,i}+(1-\beta_2)\nu_{t,i}\\
+&\ge
+\beta_2\lambda_i d_t+(1-\beta_2)\lambda_i c_t\\
+&=\lambda_i d_{t+1},
+\end{aligned}
+\]
+
+and similarly
+
+\[
+\begin{aligned}
+m_{t+1,i}
+&\le
+3\beta_2\lambda_i d_t+3(1-\beta_2)\lambda_i c_t\\
+&=3\lambda_i d_{t+1}.
+\end{aligned}
+\]
+
+This proves the first display.
+
+For the preconditioner, the first display gives
+
+\[
+d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon
+\le
+m_{t,i}+\epsilon
+\le
+3d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon.
+\]
+
+Taking inverse square roots,
+
+\[
+(3d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\le
+(m_{t,i}+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\le
+(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+Since
+
+\[
+3d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon\le 3(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon),
+\]
+
+we get
+
+\[
+\frac1{\sqrt3}(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\le
+(m_{t,i}+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\le
+(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+Finally,
+
+\[
+(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+=
+d_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/d_t)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+This proves the theorem.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Instantaneous transformed spectrum
+
+The preconditioned update is
+
+\[
+w_{t+1}=w_t-\eta_t P_t g_t,
+\]
+
+where \(P_t\) is diagonal.  If \(P_t\) were frozen during a step, the equivalent
+feature covariance would be
+
+\[
+P_t^{1/2}HP_t^{1/2}.
+\]
+
+Thus the instantaneous transformed eigenvalue is
+
+\[
+\mu_{t,i}=\lambda_iP_{t,i}.
+\]
+
+For population RMSProp, Theorem 1 gives
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\mu^{\rm pop}_{t,i}
+\asymp
+d_t^{-1/2}\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2},
+\qquad
+\rho_t=\epsilon/d_t.
+}
+\]
+
+The scalar \(d_t^{-1/2}\) rescales the learning rate.  The nontrivial spectral
+shape is therefore
+
+\[
+\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+If
+
+\[
+\lambda_i\asymp i^{-a},
+\]
+
+then there is an instantaneous damping knee
+
+\[
+m_t\asymp \rho_t^{-1/a},
+\]
+
+with
+
+\[
+\mu^{\rm shape}_{t,i}
+:=\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2}
+\asymp
+\begin{cases}
+i^{-a/2}, & i\lesssim m_t,\\[3pt]
+\rho_t^{-1/2}i^{-a}, & i\gtrsim m_t.
+\end{cases}
+\]
+
+Therefore online RMSProp has the same instantaneous two-slope spectrum as the
+frozen damped theorem with \(q=1/2\), but with time-varying damping
+\(\rho_t=\epsilon/d_t\).
+
+---
+
+## 5. Slow-drift corollary
+
+The scalar \(d_t\) is an exponential moving average of
+
+\[
+c_t=\sigma^2+\|w_t-w^\star\|_H^2.
+\]
+
+So \(d_t\) is a delayed/smoothed version of the residual scale.  If \(c_t\) does
+not change much over the RMSProp memory window, then \(d_t\asymp c_t\).
+
+### Lemma 2: slow drift of the residual scale
+
+Let
+
+\[
+\bar d_t:=\frac{d_t}{1-\beta_2^t}
+=\sum_{s=0}^{t-1}a_{t,s}c_s,
+\qquad
+ a_{t,s}:=\frac{(1-\beta_2)\beta_2^{t-1-s}}{1-\beta_2^t}.
+\]
+
+The weights \(a_{t,s}\) are nonnegative and sum to one.  If, for some \(R\ge 1\),
+
+\[
+R^{-1}c_{t-1}\le c_s\le Rc_{t-1}
+\qquad
+\text{for every }0\le s<t,
+\]
+
+then
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+R^{-1}c_{t-1}\le \bar d_t\le Rc_{t-1}.
+}
+\]
+
+More generally, if the above bound holds on the last \(L\) steps and
+\(\sum_{s<t-L}a_{t,s}\le \tau\), while \(0\le c_s\le C_{\max}\), then
+
+\[
+\bar d_t
+\le
+Rc_{t-1}+\tau C_{\max},
+\qquad
+\bar d_t
+\ge
+(1-\tau)R^{-1}c_{t-1}.
+\]
+
+### Proof
+
+The first claim follows immediately because \(\bar d_t\) is a convex combination
+of the \(c_s\).  For the second claim, split the convex combination into the last
+\(L\) steps and the older tail.  The older tail has total weight at most \(\tau\).
+
+### Consequence
+
+On a quasi-static interval where \(d_t\asymp c_t\), online RMSProp satisfies
+
+\[
+P^{\rm pop}_{t,i}
+\asymp
+c_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/c_t)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+Thus the effective damping is
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+\rho_t\asymp \epsilon/c_t
+=
+\frac{\epsilon}{\sigma^2+\|w_t-w^\star\|_H^2}.
+}
+\]
+
+As training reduces the residual scale \(c_t\), the effective damping \(\rho_t\)
+increases.  This means the range of directions that receive the flattened
+\(a/2\)-spectrum treatment can shrink over time unless \(\epsilon\) is very small.
+This gives a concrete scaling-law role to Adam/RMSProp's \(\epsilon\) parameter.
+
+---
+
+## 6. Quasi-static scaling corollary
+
+Fix a time interval \(I\) on which
+
+\[
+d_t\asymp d,
+\qquad
+\rho_t=\epsilon/d_t\asymp \rho:=\epsilon/d.
+\]
+
+Absorb the scalar \(d^{-1/2}\) into the learning rate and define the effective
+sample-size/step parameter
+
+\[
+n_I:=\sum_{t\in I}\eta_t d^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+On this interval, population online RMSProp has the same spectral filters as the
+frozen damped \(q=1/2\) theorem:
+
+\[
+\mu_i^{\rm rms}=\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+Define
+
+\[
+K_{\rho,1/2}(n_I)
+:=\#\{i:\mu_i^{\rm rms}\gtrsim n_I^{-1}\}.
+\]
+
+If \(\lambda_i\asymp i^{-a}\), then
+
+\[
+\boxed{
+K_{\rho,1/2}(n_I)
+\asymp
+\begin{cases}
+n_I^{2/a}, & n_I\lesssim \rho^{-1/2},\\[3pt]
+\rho^{-1/(2a)}n_I^{1/a}, & n_I\gtrsim \rho^{-1/2}.
+\end{cases}
+}
+\]
+
+Thus online RMSProp should show the same active-preconditioning phase as frozen
+RMSProp whenever \(\rho_t\) is approximately constant over the time scale that
+contributes most of the bias reduction.
+
+In the clean source range
+
+\[
+1<b<a/2+1,
+\]
+
+and away from the model-size bottleneck, the local risk law on such an interval
+has the same form as the frozen theorem:
+
+\[
+R-\sigma^2
+\approx
+M^{1-b}
++
+K_{\rho,1/2}(n_I)^{1-b}
++
+\frac{K_{\rho,1/2}(n_I)}{N_{\rm eff}}.
+\]
+
+This is not yet a full online-RMSProp risk theorem, because it treats the
+preconditioner as quasi-static inside the interval.  But it is the rigorous
+spectral tracking statement needed for the next theorem: a sandwich risk bound
+for online RMSProp with slowly varying \(\rho_t\).
+
+---
+
+## 7. Empirical RMSProp tracking event
+
+The theorem above uses the population EMA \(m_t\).  The raw RMSProp variable
+\(v_t\) is random.  The natural high-probability event is
+
+\[
+\mathcal E_{M,T}(\kappa):=
+\left\{
+\kappa^{-1}m_{t,i}
+\le
+v_{t,i}
+\le
+\kappa m_{t,i}
+\quad
+\text{for all }1\le i\le M,\ 1\le t\le T
+\right\}.
+\]
+
+On \(\mathcal E_{M,T}(\kappa)\), raw online RMSProp inherits the population
+spectral equivalence:
+
+\[
+(v_{t,i}+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+\asymp_{\kappa}
+(d_t\lambda_i+\epsilon)^{-1/2}
+=
+d_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\epsilon/d_t)^{-1/2}.
+\]
+
+A fully rigorous high-probability proof of \(\mathcal E_{M,T}(\kappa)\) needs
+care because \(g_{t,i}^2\) is a fourth-order Gaussian-chaos variable and raw EMA
+has heavy tails.  There are two clean routes:
+
+1. **Robust online estimator.**  Replace raw EMA by a rolling clipped or
+   median-of-means estimator.  Then \(\mathcal E_{M,T}(\kappa)\) follows from
+   blockwise concentration plus a union bound over \((i,t)\).
+2. **Conditional raw-EMA theorem.**  Prove the online risk theorem conditional on
+   \(\mathcal E_{M,T}(\kappa)\), then verify empirically that raw RMSProp
+   satisfies this event in the Gaussian power-law model for the time scales of
+   interest.
+
+For the current project, the next proof target should use route 2 first and
+route 1 as the final technical upgrade.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Next theorem target
+
+The next theorem should be a **sandwich risk theorem**.
+
+Assume that on a training horizon \([0,T]\), raw or robust online RMSProp satisfies
+
+\[
+P_{t,i}
+\asymp
+c_t^{-1/2}(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2},
+\qquad
+\rho_t=\epsilon/c_t,
+\]
+
+and that
+
+\[
+\rho_-\le \rho_t\le \rho_+.
+\]
+
+Since
+
+\[
+\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_+)^{-1/2}
+\le
+\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_t)^{-1/2}
+\le
+\lambda_i(\lambda_i+\rho_-)^{-1/2},
+\]
+
+online RMSProp should be sandwiched between two fixed damped preconditioners
+with dampings \(\rho_+\) and \(\rho_-\).  This would turn the spectral tracking
+result into a full online optimizer-dependent scaling law.
